    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1874-11-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1874-11-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="303" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d303">
                <head>No. 299.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Scott</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                    the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Honolulu</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1874-11-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">November</hi> 24, 1874</date>.
                            (Received December 29.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 300.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inform you that His
                        Majesty King Kalakaua, his suite, and Hon. H. A. Peirce, our minister
                        resident, left this <pb facs="0762" n="672" xml:id="pg_672"/> port Tuesday
                        morning last, in the United States steamer Benicia, for San Francisco, on
                        their way to Washington.* * *</p>
                <p>The King is evidently growing in the affections of his people. Some persons
                        thought there might be an effort at a revolt by the disaffected in the
                        kingdom on the departure of the King, but peace and quiet reign everywhere
                        throughout the kingdom.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>J. SCOTT.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
